          <h2 style="font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.2; font-weight: 500"> Atrocities in Tigray </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: Tigray war investigations uncover aid worker killings and widespread abuses.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Doctors Without Borders, an international health charity, accused the Ethiopian army of killing <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-spotlights-h2-3-three-of-its-workers?source=website" target="_blank">three of its workers</a> during a 2021 humanitarian mission in northern Tigray. The victims (a Spanish national and two Ethiopians) were shot at close range despite being identified as aid workers.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> The <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-spotlights-h2-4-tigray-conflict?source=website" target="_blank">Tigray conflict</a> began in 2020, after a political rift between the Tigray regional government and Ethiopia's federal authorities. What started as a power struggle quickly escalated into one of the deadliest conflicts in recent history. The fighting also involved Eritrean troops, who were supporting the Ethiopian government. Over 600,000 people died from combat, starvation, and lack of health care.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The revelation:</strong> Since the end of the Tigray war in 2022, more gruesome details have surfaced, including widespread assaults on Tigrayan women (<a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-spotlights-h2-5-more?source=website" target="_blank">more</a>, <i>warning‚Äìsensitive</i>). Meanwhile, the Eritrean government has refused to cooperate with the international investigation examining human rights violations in Tigray.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
