            "> China‚Äôs mediation project </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: China established its own mediation body, but Beijing‚Äôs troubled history raises questions about its credibility.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> China launched the <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-analysis-h1-6-international-organization-for-mediation?source=website" target="_blank">International Organization for Mediation</a> (IOMed), which aims to resolve international disputes through voluntary mediation. Representatives from 85 countries attended the launch, and approximately 33 countries signed the convention. The idea is to recommend a more flexible and less confrontational alternative to Western-led institutions, such as the International Court of Justice or the Permanent Court of Arbitration.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The challenges:</strong> Some countries see the establishment as a <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-threat-to-western-institutions?source=website" target="_blank">threat to Western institutions</a> and fear that joining a China-led initiative will be seen as an alignment with Beijing. Analysts say that the move is part of China‚Äôs wider effort to expand its influence. They question whether IOMed will be fair and impartial, as participation is voluntary, and powerful states may disregard decisions they dislike.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The bigger picture:</strong> For many countries in the Global South, IOMed could provide a platform where their voices are better heard. It could complement existing dispute mechanisms by providing states with additional options.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> However, China‚Äôs own reputation raises questions about its credibility. Its refusal to accept the 2016 arbitration <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-ruling-on-the-south-china-sea?source=website" target="_blank">ruling on the South China Sea</a> casts doubt on whether Beijing would honor IOMed‚Äôs decisions. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
