        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/turkey-renews-invasion-after-failed-peace-talks.jpg" alt="Peace talks between all the involved parties were quickly organized, but led to nothing, which made Turkey decide to invade again, only this time with overwhelming force" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>Peace talks between all the involved parties were quickly organized, but led to nothing, which made Turkey decide to invade again, this time with overwhelming force. Credits: YouTube</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> After Cyprus gained independence from Britain in 1960, power was supposed to be shared between the Greek Cypriot majority and Turkish Cypriot minority. But nationalism grew, Greek Cypriots wanted unification with Greece, while Turkish Cypriots feared losing their status and called for partition.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The intervention:</strong> In July 1974, a coup backed by Greece tried to annex Cyprus. In response, <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-foundations-h1-14-turkey-invaded?source=website" target="_blank">Turkey invaded</a> the northern part of the island, citing its rights under the <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-foundations-h1-15-1960-treaty?source=website" target="_blank">1960 Treaty</a> (an agreement allowing Britain, Greece, and Turkey to intervene to protect Cyprus‚Äôs constitutional mandate). This invasion led to the division of Cyprus, with Turkish forces occupying about one-third of the island.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The status quo:</strong> In 1983, the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus was declared, recognized by Turkey. It controls the Northern side of the Island while the Republic of Cyprus controls the south. A UN-patrolled buffer zone separates the two sides. The situation of uniting the island is rather far-fetched, as it requires compromises on both sides and addressing the concerns of both parties. Additionally, given Turkey‚Äôs <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-16-jul-25-foundations-h1-16-current-political-situation?source=website" target="_blank">current political situation</a>, the Turkish side is less likely to be interested in reaching a consensus.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
